VAs a boy in Lima,
p4
aVmy grandfather told me a legend
p5
aVof the Spanish conquest of Peru.
p6
aVAtahualpa, emperor of the Inca, had been captured and killed.
p7
aVPizarro and his conquistadors had grown rich,
p8
aVand tales of their conquest and glory had reached Spain
p9
aVand was bringing new waves of Spaniards, hungry for gold and glory.
p10
aVThey would go into towns and ask the Inca,
p11
aV"Where's another civilization we can conquer? Where's more gold?"
p12
aa(lp13
VAnd the Inca, out of vengeance, told them,
p14
aV"Go to the Amazon.
p15
aVYou'll find all the gold you want there.
p16
aVIn fact, there is a city called Paititi \u2014 El Dorado in Spanish \u2014
p17
aVmade entirely of gold."
p18
aa(lp19
VThe Spanish set off into the jungle,
p20
aVbut the few that return come back with stories,
p21
aVstories of powerful shamans,
p22
aVof warriors with poisoned arrows,
p23
aVof trees so tall they blotted out the sun,
p24
aVspiders that ate birds, snakes that swallowed men whole
p25
aVand a river that boiled.
p26
aa(lp27
VAll this became a childhood memory.
p28
aVAnd years passed.
p29
aVI'm working on my PhD at SMU,
p30
aVtrying to understand Peru's geothermal energy potential,
p31
aVwhen I remember this legend,
p32
aVand I began asking that question.
p33
aVCould the boiling river exist?
p34
aa(lp35
VI asked colleagues from universities,
p36
aVthe government,
p37
aVoil, gas and mining companies,
p38
aVand the answer was a unanimous no.
p39
aVAnd this makes sense.
p40
aVYou see, boiling rivers do exist in the world,
p41
aVbut they're generally associated with volcanoes.
p42
aVYou need a powerful heat source
p43
aVto produce such a large geothermal manifestation.
p44
aVAnd as you can see from the red dots here, which are volcanoes,
p45
aVwe don't have volcanoes in the Amazon,
p46
aVnor in most of Peru.
p47
aVSo it follows: We should not expect to see a boiling river.
